I don’t think I’d written 15 minutes before I was reading exceptionally hard and had to shed a layer, even though it wasn’t that warm. The course was pretty muddy, so I only rode one lap even though I would have liked to get a second one in. It is rooty, which won’t be bad if they are dry, but as it was, traction was a major issue. It is a punching force, with lots of power moves to get over roots especially when wet. The first climb is pretty steep gravel going into the trail, then about five or six steep switchbacks till it levels out the first time. Title: Mohican 100k
AthleteComments: *05/22/2022 Abigail Snyder: Legs felt pretty dead/dull all day. That 5 mile road start with the crazy hill to start it is terrible for someone like me in a mass start. I got behind an enormous congo line of riders going into the singletrack and got stopped up more times that I can count. Small successes: I rode the rock garden and super steep hill in the Mohican SP without getting stopped. I ran out of water before Aid 2, so had to make an unplanned (but definitely smart) stop there for more bottles. My handlebars came loose, so stopped again to fix those and re-tighten my stem plate. Slid out and crashed on a root that I had plenty of traction over while pre-riding…. I had zero rear wheel traction (note: don’t ride the Rekon Race in slimy conditions. It’s useless). Chose to run the Mohican wilderness rock garden based on pre-ride, and was pretty much just spitting mad by time I popped out at aid 3. Ate some chips, drank an icee, got my glasses cleaned and chain lubed (thanks Aaron!) and felt generally better going into the last 1/3 of the race. Gave it everything I had, but still didn’t see any more women and suspected I was so far back from my slow pull through the state park that I didn’t have any chance at the podium, but figured I was going to “go for the brick” anyway and leave it all out there. Ended in 3rd. Other side note re: fit. I can get into a comfortable aero position on my hardtail, but cannot fit into that position on the Epic. Togs were helpful, but not really game changers. Need to try different grips (maybe Ergon or ESI super chunky) to alleviate blistering on outer palms.*

Title: UCI World Cup: Snowshoe XCO
AthleteComments: *08/01/2022 Abigail Snyder: Oof. Surprised myself at the start by being able to hang onto the pack. Nailed the drop both laps. Got taken out by Sydney crashing in front of me right at the beginning of the course. Managed to get up and catch back up to the pack. Was sending "P" (downhill trail) when I ran into the back of a train of walkers...had to walk. Then for whatever reason I couldn't get back into my pedal....fought with it for the entire next section of trail before I finally got clipped back in...which meant I got dropped WAY off the back. Finally got pedaling again and was feeling good and sending it, then crashed HARD on a muddy descent. Again, got back up and kept riding. Even rode the rock garden no problems (with my bars crooked!). Stopped at pits to let Steve straighten my bars. Had to step down on "P" when I got off-line. Lost traction on ensuing climb and had to walk again. So frustrating. Nailed the descent that I crashed on the first time. Stepped down on rock garden when getting off line. Got pulled after two laps. 35th place. Still got UCI points. I'll take it.*

Title: SPRINTS INTO SHORT THRESHOLD EFFORTS
WorkoutDescription: STAND INTO A SPRINT AND THEN REMAIN WORKING IN THE THRESHOLD RANGE FOR 2-3 PLUS MINUTES FOLLOWING THE SPRINT - GENERAL ENDURANCE BETWEEN EFFORTS - Warm up today into the 130HR range checking bio feedback- if your feeling any fatigue or increased breath, add more warm up - Whenever your feeling it, nuke it into a 20-30 second sprint - All out, be safe with it - Then following the sprint, keep the motor going, working a threshold effort, like gaping a rider in a race - 165-175HR - for power lets see your best 3-5 min output - 270-290 Plus Watts - Work a few efforts close together, space a few apart to recover, keep the spin between efforts in the 120-140 HR range and aim for 4-6 of these efforts today or more
CoachComments: WORK ON FEEL, SPRINT AS BEST YOU CAN, KEEP IT SIMPLE THEN WORK AN EFFORT - IF IT STARTS TO HURT, JUST BACK OFF - THE INDOOR WORKOUT ABOVE IS MEANT FOR THE TRAINER, WHEN OUTSIDE USE YOUR TERRAIN TO WORK EFFORTS, DOESN'T NEED TO BE DONE PERFECTLY

I really enjoyed being able to use the trail to push myself on the climbs, then hold the threshold until a true descent. It will definitely take me a bit to get used to looking at my computer a bit more until I get a good gauge on heart rate and time. I’m so used to it beeping at me to start and finish, and when I’m under or over power. Lol*

Title: 1 MIN POWER EFFORTS INTO TEMPO
WorkoutDescription: NUKE IT INTO ALL OUT ONE MIN EFFORTS FOLLOWED BY SEATED TEMPO SPIN - Warm up into the 130's, checking how you feel as always. When feeling fluid and good, find a short hill or slight uphill grade and NUKE it into an all out one min efforts, standing/seated - Don't worry about HR for these - Power goal - 300-400 plus watts - After the effort recover if needed or not and immediately spin into a seated tempo effort anywhere in the 150-160 HR range - Cap HR at 160 for this these efforts and work the effort up to 5-10 plus minutes - If on a longer hill, up to 20 min - Steady fun spin between today - Add a few short 5-6 sec sprints in the mix as well - Aim for 3-6 or more good power/tempo efforts today.
CoachComments: GET HR UNDER 160 AFTER THE HARD EFFORT AND SPIN TEMPO REMEMBER, USE THE STRUCTURED STUFF INDOORS, OUTSIDE USE YOUR TERRAIN AND WORK AS MANY OR AS FEW EFFORTS YOU FEEL YOU NEED - ITS GOOD TO PUSH LIMITS, ITS ALSO GOOD TO LISTEN TO YOURSELF

Title: TEMPO INTO SUB LT
WorkoutDescription: EASE INTO LONGER SEATED TEMPO EFFORTS TODAY - FINISH EACH TEMPO EFFORT WITH A FEW MINUTES OF SUB THRESHOLD SPIN - Warm up as usual, checking bio feedback - Add more warm up if needed - When ready, pick up speed and power and ease into a tempo pace effort in the 150-160 HR range - Power goal can be 220-240 plus watts - Aim for longer 7-10 min, up to 20 min efforts - At the end of the tempo effort, up the pace into the Sub threshold HR and power ranges for an additional 3-5 minutes - HR can rise into the 160-170 range, power can be 240-260 plus watts - Space these efforts by at least 10-15 min with steady fluid spin anywhere in the 130-140's - Aim for 3-5 solid, longer efforts here today
CoachComments: WORK SEATED AND WITH A FAST LEG SPEED TODAY - LONG STRETCHES OF ROAD AND TRAIL, HAVE FUN WITH IT, GOOD COMBO TO WORK RIGHT NOW

Have a fun ride.

Title: SEATED TO STANDING FORCE INTO TEMPO
WorkoutDescription: GET INTO SEATED FORCE EFFORTS ON CLIMBS, FINISHING THE EFFORT STANDING - WORK SOME TEMPO BETWEEN A FEW EFFORTS - Warm up into the 130's HR, check how you feel - When ready, on a climb, shift a gear or two harder (or use a single speed) remain seated and grind a 20-30 second effort, then stand and continue that effort for another 20-30 seconds - Efforts can be shorter 30-60 seconds or longer 2-5 plus minute efforts, just work the seated to standing theme - HR can rise into the 160's-170's, Power 400-500 watt range - cadence 50-70 rpm but focus more on grinding an effort - Sit and spin into tempo ranges, 150-160HR between a few efforts today, otherwise spin easier, 140's, to recover.
CoachComments: 90 MIN INSIDE - IF OUTDOORS DOESN'T NEED TO BE THIS PERFECT, JUST WORK FORCE, HILLS, SOME TEMPO - THEME FOR THE DAY

Title: TEMPO ON CLIMBS/FEW SPRINTS TO END

Title: MID RIDE SUB -THRESHOLD CAPPED WITH TEMPO EFFORTS
WorkoutDescription: WORK INTO SHORT AND LONG THRESHOLD EFFORTS TODAY MID RIDE - KEEP IT SIMPLE - CAP THE DAY WITH TEMPO EFFORTS - take your time warming up as always. Ease into the 130 HR range and check your bio feedback - If you have any fatigue today while warming up, add more warm up spin before efforts - To start the day, spin into tempo efforts, one longer 10 plus minute or shorter efforts if outside, HR 150-160, power 250 plus watts - Steady spin for a little then nuke some harder threshold efforts mid ride - Choose stretches of road or trail for an effort, seated and standing, spin it into SUB threshold ranges, 160-170 HR range - Short or longer efforts, from a minute to 5 plus minutes - Power goals can be 260 plus watts for efforts - End of ride, work more tempo, short and long efforts or one longer effort 10 plus minutes
CoachComments: RAMP UP TO SOME EFFORTS TODAY MID RIDE - IF THE LEGS ARE SORE, PE IS HIGH BAG THE HARDER EFFORTS, STEADY SPIN IT OUT
AthleteComments: *12/19/2022 Abigail Snyder: The last three miles were a death march. SO TIRED. Holding tempo was about all I could do on the last climb, but I tried to push the last bit into subLT. That being said, lungs are feeling way better.*

Title: STEADY ENDURANCE
WorkoutDescription: STEADY PACE IN THE 140-155 RANGES MAINLY WITH FEW BREAKS - WORK WITH A SLIGHTLY FASTER CADENCE THE WHOLE TIME TODAY - Warm up and ride into the 130-140 ranges. Check your bio feedback here. Where is your breath? Where is your PE? How do your legs feel? If you feel good fatigue, add more warm up and back off the ranges for the day- If you feel good then spin in the 140-155 range for most of the ride today - Spin seated with a slightly faster cadence today, all day long - Add easier spin breaks when needed - If normal cadence is in the 85RPM range, aim for 90 plus on longer segments
CoachComments: FLUID SPIN, CAN BE LONGER, JUST GO FOR IT - TAP ON THE PEDALS, KEEP IT FUN
AthleteComments: *12/21/2022 Abigail Snyder: Meeting ran long this morning, and the first ride on the trainer is always a bit of a cluster (I forgot a water bottle, snacks, etc., had to readjust the fan, figure out the connectivity/Zwift set up, etc.). Ran out of time before I needed to be back at work to finish out the 90 min. Struggled a little to get HR up, but was also struggling to get "into" the Zwift ride. It'll come...it just takes me a minute to engage.*

Title: TEMPO ON CLIMBS/FEW SPRINTS TO END
WorkoutDescription: GOAL IS TO WORK IN A STEADY FLOW, HR IN THE 150-160 RANGES, WITH FEWER BREAKS - SPIN SMOOTH AND WITH A NATURAL, SLIGHTLY FASTER CADENCE - ON CLIMBS, HOLD TEMPO RANGES BUT KEEP IT THERE - Warm up into the 140's HR and check bio feedback as always, if feeling greater fatigue, higher PE, add more warm up - When feeling good, get into a steady fluid endurance pace today in the 140-155HR ranges - Keep breath deep and tap on the pedals - On all climbs, tempo spin it, 150-160 HR range, as much speed and power but cap HR at 165 - Keep it this simple all day, with fewer breaks. - END OF RIDE, WORK IN 2-3 30-40 SECOND SPRINTS, RAMPING UP TO ALL OUT IN THE LAST 10 SECONDS OF THE SPRINT - If outdoors spring in safe places!
CoachComments: GET THE LEGS SPINNING FLUID, FEW SPRINTS - KEEP IT SIMPLE TODAY
AthleteComments: *12/22/2022 Abigail Snyder: The power targets in the structured workout felt really hard. That being said, the first few workouts on the trainer always feel hard--and I feel a little like I'm still finding my position and mindset on the trainer yet.* *12/22/2022 Abigail Snyder: The structured workout that was built in was 90 min, but time said 2 hours. Not sure... do I do the structured workout, then just free ride for the rest of the time, or extend the workout with additional reps to fill the 2 hours?*

Title: EverAthlete: RideStrong Stability
AthleteComments: *12/24/2022 Abigail Snyder: Harder than I expected. Left shoulder blade has a huge knot in it post-workout too. Going to try and spend some time mobilizing it tomorrow.*

Title: LONG TEMPO EFFORTS
WorkoutDescription: FOCUS ON STEADY SPIN IN THE 150-160 RANGE FOR 10-30 MINUTE PERIODS - STEADY EASIER SPINNING BETWEEN EFFORTS - Warm up and ride into the 130HR ranges, add a few jumps, get the system going - Check your bio feedback here. When warmed up and ready, choose sections of trail or roads, especially on the hill grades and climbs, and spin mainly seated into the 150-160HR ranges for duration s of 10-20 plus minutes - Power goal can be 230 - 250 watts, just keep HR under 165 - If you feel good and can work up to 30 min efforts, go for it - Easier, steady spin for between all efforts today, 130-140's HR - Work efforts on and off all day until speed and power drops - If speed or power doesn't drop, work these all day and have fun with it - Remember, push speed and power, keep breath deep and HR in line
CoachComments: BE FLUID - KEEP HR IN LINE, PUSH POWER IF FEELING GOOD
AthleteComments: *12/24/2022 Abigail Snyder: Oof. Longest ride on the trainer in a minute. Did one 30-min effort, then two shorter efforts. Felt decent overall, though definitely tired of sitting in one spot by the end. lol. (Broke it up by doing one "race" -- at tempo -- then continuing to ride).*

Title: ABOVE/BELOW - TEMPO, SUB LT
WorkoutDescription: ONCE INTO A FLUID PACE, WORK BETWEEN SHORT TEMPO AND SUB LT EFFORTS ALL DAY - FLUID STEADY SPIN REST OF THE DAY - Warm up into the 140's as usual, checking feedback and adding more warm up if needed - When ready, spin into a tempo effort, 150-160HR - Push power here but keep HR under 165 - Work here for 3-5 minutes, seated spin - Then up the intensity, over 160 HR up to 170 HR for 3-5 minutes - Power goal can be 250-270 watt range for this part of the effort - Then lower intensity back under 160 and work back into tempo ranges - Keep this above and below 160 going for as long as you can, can be 10 min, 20 min or the whole day - When needed, spin in the 140's to recover
CoachComments: BE FLUID, HAVE FUN, AND FOCUS THESE EFFORTS ON HILLS AND SOME FLATS, SEATED, STANDING
AthleteComments: *12/26/2022 Abigail Snyder: Overslept and did not have time to get 2 1/2 hours in, even if I would have had the legs. My legs are heavy and sore from the different stimulus of the trainer. I couldn’t seem to pedal hard enough to hit either the power or heart rate goals for sub LT*

Title: EASY SPIN / SINGLE LEG DRILLS
WorkoutDescription: KEEP IT EASY TODAY AND SPIN IN THE 130-150HR RANGE KEEP IT EASY AND LIGHT AND WORK WITH A NATURAL CADENCE ---- keep today to a steady spin in the 130-150 ranges where you feel comfortable spinning. No need to push it today.Try to keep 130 as a minimum HR range to maintain. On flats/hills, un-clip at times and spin one leg for 30 seconds, switch legs then back to easy spin - Add these when appropriate, on safe terrain, away from autos.
CoachComments: EASY 60-90 MINUTES - TAKE IT EASY, SAVE IT FOR THE REST OF THE WEEK
AthleteComments: *12/26/2022 Abigail Snyder: Switching to Thursday because I think the group training ride I was asked to lead on Wednesday will be a bit hard for this.* *12/29/2022 Abigail Snyder: I am NOT smooth at single leg drills. Lol. Fell on my butt because I couldn’t get my pedal out. Otherwise a good day.*

Title: FORCE WORK - TEMPO
WorkoutDescription: JAM OUT FORCE EFFORTS TODAY FOR THE MAJORITY OF THE RIDE - SHIFT HARDER GEARS AND GRIND OUT EFFORTS - Warm up into the 130's HR, check how you feel - When ready, early ride, shift a gear or two harder (or use a single speed) and grind a few hills - Just get into the effort, can be shorter 30-60 seconds or longer 1-5 plus minute efforts - HR can rise into the 160's-170's, cadence 50-70 rpm but focus more on grinding an effort over power and HR - Work force efforts throughout the day with a few seated tempo spin efforts, HR into the 150-160HR range - Power goal can be 230-250 plus watt range for these efforts - Keep the spin between everything today steady and fun, 130-140's.
CoachComments: 60-90 MIN INSIDE - IF OUTDOORS DOESN'T NEED TO BE THIS PERFECT, ITS A SINGLE SPEED OR FORCE FOCUSED RIDE, WORK THE LEGS AND CORE ON THE BIKE
AthleteComments: *12/29/2022 Abigail Snyder: Swapping this from Saturday, as I'm less likely to be able to ride Saturday due to family plans... and am planning to get a solid 2 hour ride in en route on Friday.* *12/30/2022 Abigail Snyder: Ended up riding entirely on pavement. Tried to get the force work in on the climbs. Felt pretty good today. Beautiful roads.*
